  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\"><em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> (Peter Lang Verlag, 2019), edited by Charlotte Ashby, Grace Brockington, Daniel Laqua, and Sarah Victoria Turner, is an edited volume situated at the intersection of art history, political internationalism, and cultural exchange. The book holds a citation percentile of approximately 72 among comparable works, and its commercial presence across major retail and reader platforms signals engagement beyond strictly academic circles. Scholarly uptake remains in its early stages, with one recorded citation to date.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\"><em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> intervenes in a historiographical conversation about how the arts functioned within internationalist projects \u2014 including bodies such as the League of Nations \u2014 as vehicles for negotiating national identity and fostering cultural exchange across borders. The editors bring together perspectives from art history, political science, and sociology to examine how cosmopolitan ideals were imagined, staged, and sometimes contested through aesthetic practice. The volume's conceptual map, weighted heavily toward internationalism in politics, national identity, and historiography, positions it as a scholarly resource for readers working across the history of art and the history of international relations.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book is the second volume in Peter Lang's <em>Internationalism and the Arts</em> series, a sequence that extends from Andrzej Szczerski's <em>Views of Albion</em> (2015) through Charlotte Ashby's <em>Nordic Design in Translation</em> (2023) and Samuel Shaw's <em>Art, Identity and Cosmopolitanism</em> (2024). This series context is meaningful: <em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> helped consolidate the series' intellectual identity at a formative stage, and Ashby's continued editorial presence across multiple volumes suggests a sustained research program rather than a one-off intervention. Daniel Laqua emerges from the volume's internal network data as the author with the clearest continued scholarly footprint within this area.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's single recorded citation \u2014 a 2021 article in <em>British Art Studies</em> by Liz Bruchet and Ming Tiampo, affiliated with Carleton University and University College London respectively \u2014 is instructive about where the volume's ideas have traveled. That article, examining contrapuntal histories between imperialism and decolonization at the Slade School of Fine Art, draws on <em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> in a framework centered on decolonization, empire, and narrative. The connection is telling: the book's engagement with cosmopolitanism and cultural exchange across national boundaries speaks directly to postcolonial reassessments of international art institutions. The citing work itself has attracted substantial scholarly attention, suggesting that <em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> has found a productive niche within a lively and growing critical discourse.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Library holdings verified through WorldCat catalogue the book under the subjects of cultural relations and the history of the arts, and it has been acquired by at least four institutions. The volume's commercial presence on general-reader platforms broadens its potential audience beyond specialist libraries. An alignment with the Sustainable Development Goal of reduced inequalities \u2014 while modest in confidence score \u2014 is consistent with the book's attention to how international cultural frameworks can entrench or challenge asymmetries of power and representation. Taken together, these signals portray <em>Imagined Cosmopolis</em> as a steady scholarly contribution whose influence is still accumulating, particularly among historians working at the intersection of art, empire, and internationalist thought.</p>",
